An analytic method for longitudinal mortality studies.

Strauss D(1), Shavelle R, DeVivo MJ, Day S.

Author information:
(1)Department of Statistics, University of California, Riverside, CA 92521-0138, 
USA.

Our knowledge of mortality risks comes largely from longitudinal (cohort) 
studies. The most commonly used analytic tool is the Cox proportional hazards 
model for survival analysis. An alternative approach is a simple cross-sectional 
analysis of person-years. The key to the method is logistic regression, where 
the outcome variable is lived/died in the given year and the explanatory 
variables are age, sex, and other potential risk factors. This approach can be 
used to model any dichotomous outcome and has several important advantages over 
the more traditional survival analysis. As an example, we compare the two 
methods using a large data base of patients with spinal cord injury.

